Methodology
1. Data Cleaning & Preparation
Removed duplicate and incomplete records
Standardized categorical fields
Prepared customer segmentation labels
Converted survey responses into analytical datasets
2. NPS Classification

Customers were categorized as:

Promoters: Ratings 9–10
Passives: Ratings 7–8
Detractors: Ratings 0–6
NPS Formula

NPS=%Promoters−%Detractors

Final NPS Results
Promoters: 45%
Passives: 26%
Detractors: 30%
Overall NPS: +15

The analysis revealed that the customer experience was positive overall but vulnerable due to recurring concerns around pricing and renewal communication.

Key Insights
1. Pricing Was the Biggest Driver of Dissatisfaction

Text analysis showed that customers frequently mentioned:

Rising premiums
Unclear price increases
Poor value perception
Lack of loyalty rewards

Long-term customers especially felt penalized despite not making claims.

2. Claim Usage Strongly Influenced Satisfaction

Customers who had used insurance services were significantly more satisfied than those who had never claimed.

Customer Type	NPS
Claimed Members	27
Non-Claimed Members	7

This indicated that customers who never used the service struggled to perceive ongoing value from their insurance plans.

3. Renewal Experience Impacted Customer Loyalty

The analysis found:

Auto-renew customers had the highest satisfaction
Customers confused about renewal processes had the lowest ratings
Poor communication during renewal negatively impacted customer trust

Customers who did not understand how their renewal worked consistently produced lower satisfaction scores.

4. Long-Tenure Customers Were High-Risk Segments

Customers with 10+ years of tenure frequently expressed dissatisfaction due to:

Rising premium costs
Lack of loyalty recognition
Weak communication regarding value

This highlighted the importance of retention-focused customer engagement strategies.

